Stimulus Specification:
Stimulus Type Description:

{
  "line_min": 0,
  "line_max": 8,
  "points": [
    {
      "value": 1.0,
      "label": "$\\frac{\\sqrt{9}}{3}$"
    },
    {
      "value": 6.283185307179586,
      "label": "$2\\pi$"
    }
  ]
}

Question Requirements:
- The stem MUST describe a **real-world savings goal** with: - a **total cost** (or goal amount) in dollars, - an **amount already saved**, - a **conditional amount** that **may or may not** be received (scholarship, grant, donation, rebate), - a fixed number of **months** for equal monthly savings. - The stem MUST state that the family (or group) will set aside a **fixed amount each month** for the stated number of months - The question MUST ask **“How much should [person/group] save each month for the next [n] months to have enough money to [pay for / buy / cover] …?”** - Instruction MUST include: **“Move the correct answer to each box. Not all answers will be used.”** - **Five** draggable dollar amounts (format **$___** or **$__.__**); **exactly two** are correct. - **Two inline drop boxes** embedded in **complete sentences**, one for each conditional scenario: - If [person] **receives / wins** the [scholarship/grant/etc.], … save a minimum of **[ ]** per month. - If [person] **does not receive / does not win** … save a minimum of **[ ]** per month. - **Correct monthly savings:** - **With** conditional amount: **(total − saved − conditional) ÷ months** - **Without** conditional amount: **(total − saved) ÷ months** - **Distractors** SHOULD include: **total ÷ months** without subtracting savings (e.g. **$1,250** in **2023 Item 15**); an amount from **incorrect subtraction**; a **partial** monthly value.
### Inline Drag and Drop — canonical JSON (COPY THIS SHAPE)
Output MUST match this structure. **Do not omit any key shown below.** The #1 validation failure is a missing `placeholder` on **the second target** (`targets[1].target.placeholder`).
```json
{
  "question": "<context paragraph>\nMove the correct answer to each box. Not all answers will be used.\n<interaction>If [Name] receives the [grant/scholarship/…], [group] will need to save a minimum of <target-1> per month. If [Name] does not receive the [grant/scholarship/…], [group] will need to save a minimum of <target-2> per month.</interaction>",
  "targets": [
    {
      "id": "t1",
      "label": "With [funding type] monthly amount",
      "target": { "placeholder": "<target-1>" }
    },
    {
      "id": "t2",
      "label": "Without [funding type] monthly amount",
      "target": { "placeholder": "<target-2>" }
    }
  ],
  "choices": [
    { "id": "c1", "text": "$700",  "matchMax": 1 },
    { "id": "c2", "text": "$850",  "matchMax": 1 },
    { "id": "c3", "text": "$1,200", "matchMax": 1 },
    { "id": "c4", "text": "$950",  "matchMax": 1 },
    { "id": "c5", "text": "$600",  "matchMax": 1 }
  ],
  "correctMapping": [
    {
      "choiceId": "c1",
      "targetId": "t1",
      "explanation": { "title": "Great job!", "text": "With funding: subtract saved and conditional from total, then divide by months." }
    },
    {
      "choiceId": "c2",
      "targetId": "t2",
      "explanation": { "title": "Nice work!", "text": "Without funding: subtract saved from total, then divide by months." }
    }
  ],

Stimulus Specification:
Use `draw_equal_perimeter_shapes` when a problem needs a diagram showing two geometric shapes whose perimeters are compared or stated to be equal.

The function draws two shapes side by side with algebraic side-length labels and congruence tick marks. It supports:
- `triangle`
- `square`
- `rectangle`

Provide this input shape:

{
  "left": {
    "shape_type": "triangle" | "square" | "rectangle",
    "side_labels": [...]
  },
  "right": {
    "shape_type": "triangle" | "square" | "rectangle",
    "side_labels": [...]
  },
  "unit": "yd" | "in." | "cm" | "m" | ...
}

Side-label rules:
- For `triangle`, provide exactly 3 labels in this order:
  `[left side, top-right side, bottom side]`
- For `square`, provide exactly 1 label:
  `[side length]`
- For `rectangle`, provide exactly 2 labels:
  `[horizontal length, vertical width]`

Do not include the unit inside `side_labels`; put the unit only in the top-level `unit` field. For example, use `"2x"` with `"unit": "cm"`, not `"2x cm"`.

Example, triangle + square:

{
  "left": {
    "shape_type": "triangle",
    "side_labels": ["2x", "(4x - 2)", "2(x + 7)"]
  },
  "right": {
    "shape_type": "square",
    "side_labels": ["2.5x"]
  },
  "unit": "yd"
}

Example, triangle + rectangle:

{
  "left": {
    "shape_type": "triangle",
    "side_labels": ["3x", "(2x + 1)", "(x + 5)"]
  },
  "right": {
    "shape_type": "rectangle",
    "side_labels": ["(2x - 1)", "x"]
  },
  "unit": "cm"
}

Expected output:
The function returns an image file path. The image is a clean black-and-white line drawing with the two shapes side by side. Side labels appear outside the shapes. Squares show matching tick marks on all four sides. Rectangles show matching tick marks on opposite sides, with different tick styles for length and width. Triangles are drawn as scalene triangles with all three sides labeled.

Use this function only for visual diagrams. The function does not solve for `x` and does not verify that the perimeters are actually equal; the problem author or LLM must choose algebraic expressions that match the intended math.
